665
01:17:12,346 --> 01:17:13,836
Deserters.

666
01:17:14,281 --> 01:17:15,771
Replacements.

667
01:17:28,529 --> 01:17:32,021
Tote arms!

668
01:17:39,740 --> 01:17:40,934
Come back.

669
01:17:42,209 --> 01:17:43,938
Stick together!

670
01:17:47,047 --> 01:17:49,345
Stick together and we'll be all right.

671
01:17:50,518 --> 01:17:52,247
And be ready for them.

672
01:18:17,945 --> 01:18:19,310
Turn around, lads!

673
01:18:19,580 --> 01:18:22,105
-Don't go any farther.
-Come on, lads. Turn around.

674
01:18:22,183 --> 01:18:24,515
Pigs to the slaughter! Look at you!

675
01:18:24,752 --> 01:18:26,242
Turn around, lads.

676
01:18:48,209 --> 01:18:49,471
Listen, lads.

677
01:18:50,311 --> 01:18:52,711
Ten miles up that road are the Germans!

678
01:18:54,481 --> 01:18:56,346
-Rubbish.
-Not rubbish.

679
01:18:56,450 --> 01:18:59,442
They're coming. And they're coming fast.

680
01:19:00,421 --> 01:19:02,013
You've let them in.

681
01:19:04,325 --> 01:19:06,316
They're coming for your wives...

682
01:19:06,460 --> 01:19:08,758
...your houses, your country.

683
01:19:08,896 --> 01:19:11,330
Your country, Officer!

684
01:19:12,132 --> 01:19:15,158
Yes, my country! And proud--

685
01:19:30,251 --> 01:19:31,946
Get back in your ranks!

686
01:19:32,820 --> 01:19:34,412
Get back in your ranks!

687
01:19:40,227 --> 01:19:41,694
Get back!

688
01:19:44,598 --> 01:19:46,759
Get back in the ranks!

689
01:21:02,843 --> 01:21:04,174
Are you a nurse?

690
01:21:05,012 --> 01:21:05,944
Yes.

691
01:21:06,046 --> 01:21:07,707
-Are you all right?
-Yes.

692
01:21:08,449 --> 01:21:09,848
Then help me.

693
01:21:37,978 --> 01:21:41,345
Doctor, l ought to tell you,
l'm not a trained nurse, l'm a volunteer.

694
01:21:41,415 --> 01:21:42,609
l see. Right.

695
01:21:43,550 --> 01:21:45,142
Why did you volunteer?

696
01:21:45,853 --> 01:21:48,788
-l came here to find my husband.
-Very gently.

697
01:21:49,223 --> 01:21:51,589
-Have you ever seen an operation?
-Yes.

698
01:21:51,759 --> 01:21:53,021
We'll manage.

699
01:22:05,606 --> 01:22:09,098
They're in the next village, brothers.
The Germans.

700
01:22:10,344 --> 01:22:12,039
-Your Honor--
-Keep still.

701
01:22:42,109 --> 01:22:44,043
Did you find your husband?

702
01:22:45,479 --> 01:22:46,468
No.

703
01:22:46,580 --> 01:22:47,911
Your Honor....

704
01:22:48,048 --> 01:22:49,709
Yes, we'd better be off.

705
01:23:06,133 --> 01:23:09,068
You know, you often look at me
as though you knew me.

706
01:23:09,269 --> 01:23:12,432
l have seen you.
Four years ago. Christmas Eve.

707
01:23:14,808 --> 01:23:16,366
Were you there?

708
01:23:17,311 --> 01:23:19,006
No wonder you look at me.

709
01:23:20,981 --> 01:23:22,972
Did you know Victor Komarovsky?

710
01:23:23,617 --> 01:23:26,814
Yes, l did. That young man,
who took you away--

711
01:23:26,920 --> 01:23:27,818
My husband.

712
01:23:27,888 --> 01:23:31,051
A lot of courage.
He made the rest of us look very feeble.

713
01:23:31,124 --> 01:23:33,752
As a matter of fact, l thought you both did.

714
01:23:34,094 --> 01:23:35,823
Good man to shoot at.

715
01:23:36,864 --> 01:23:39,264
l'd give anything never to have met him.

716
01:24:09,530 --> 01:24:11,225
The tsar's in prison.

717
01:24:13,200 --> 01:24:14,724
Lenin's in Moscow.

718
01:24:16,203 --> 01:24:17,966
Civil war has started.

719
01:24:18,372 --> 01:24:19,339
Good!

720
01:24:19,406 --> 01:24:20,964
Civil war, good?

721
01:24:21,875 --> 01:24:24,070
Not good, Comrade Nurse, inevitable.

722
01:24:25,712 --> 01:24:28,704
But Lenin in Moscow!

723
01:24:29,383 --> 01:24:32,875
This Lenin, will he be the new tsar then?

724
01:24:33,987 --> 01:24:37,423
Listen, Daddy.
No more tsars, no more masters.

725
01:24:37,724 --> 01:24:41,125
Only workers in a worker's state.
How about that?

726
01:24:42,462 --> 01:24:43,952
Are you a doctor?

727
01:24:44,164 --> 01:24:45,859
-Yes.
-Follow me, please.

728
01:25:32,713 --> 01:25:34,647
l can't deal with this.

729
01:25:35,182 --> 01:25:38,674
Order of the Provisional Government.
You'll have to try, friend.

730
01:25:46,827 --> 01:25:49,489
''lf you could see how hard
we have been working here...

731
01:25:49,563 --> 01:25:53,021
''...l feel sure you'd forgive me, dear,
for not writing more regularly.''

732
01:25:53,100 --> 01:25:54,465
When was that written?

733
01:25:54,568 --> 01:25:55,830
July 20th.

734
01:25:55,902 --> 01:25:57,062
Eight weeks!

735
01:25:57,638 --> 01:26:00,334
''But now the war seems
really to have stopped.

736
01:26:00,407 --> 01:26:03,672
''The hospital is emptying,
and l shall have more time.

737
01:26:03,777 --> 01:26:08,111
''l may even get time to write some verse,
if l've not forgotten how to.''

738
01:26:08,715 --> 01:26:10,182
Oh, l do hope so!

739
01:26:12,452 --> 01:26:16,013
''Larissa Antipova is still here,
and l admire her more and more.

740
01:26:17,758 --> 01:26:22,127
''She seems to have the strange gift
of healing, which doctors don't believe in.

741
01:26:22,863 --> 01:26:26,799
''She often does the wrong things,
but it always seems to work out right.

742
01:26:28,435 --> 01:26:29,902
''How is Uncle Alex?

743
01:26:30,070 --> 01:26:33,471
-''Can he still get his English tobacco?''
-Would that he could!

744
01:26:33,540 --> 01:26:36,703
''Can Sasha say his letters yet?
And how is Auntie Anna?''

745
01:26:38,311 --> 01:26:40,176
He didn't get my letter.

746
01:26:41,348 --> 01:26:43,839
''Most of all, my dearest, how are you?''

747
01:26:44,451 --> 01:26:47,113
Strangely upsetting.
He doesn't know she's dead.

748
01:26:48,388 --> 01:26:50,515
Can't see what difference it makes.

749
01:26:51,892 --> 01:26:53,359
They're at it again!

750
01:26:54,061 --> 01:26:56,552
l wish they'd decide once and for all...

751
01:26:57,164 --> 01:27:01,931
...which gang of hooligans constitutes
the government of this country!

752
01:27:08,775 --> 01:27:10,242
Cheer up, Sergei.

753
01:27:11,111 --> 01:27:12,840
Don't you want to go home?

754
01:27:13,613 --> 01:27:16,480
There's fighting at home, Your Honor.
l've had enough.

755
01:27:17,117 --> 01:27:21,076
Red Guards and White Guards,
this old man's had enough.

756
01:27:22,556 --> 01:27:24,547
Your Honor is a kind gentleman.

757
01:27:27,294 --> 01:27:29,558
And, the nurse is a kind lady.

758
01:27:44,578 --> 01:27:45,738
Finished?

759
01:27:45,979 --> 01:27:47,310
Just about.

760
01:27:56,289 --> 01:27:58,951
ln a couple of weeks
you'll be with your little girl.

761
01:27:59,025 --> 01:28:00,686
lf l can get on a train.

762
01:28:03,697 --> 01:28:06,860
l want to be with Katya
more than anything in the world.

763
01:28:07,134 --> 01:28:08,396
Yes, of course.

764
01:28:09,903 --> 01:28:12,201
But, now that we're going, l feel sad.

765
01:28:14,374 --> 01:28:15,363
Sad.

766
01:28:16,710 --> 01:28:17,802
Really sad.

767
01:28:18,445 --> 01:28:20,777
-Well, we've been here some time.
-Yes.

768
01:28:23,450 --> 01:28:25,941
This must have been a lovely house, once.

769
01:28:26,887 --> 01:28:28,047
Don't you think?

770
01:28:28,121 --> 01:28:29,884
What are you going to do?

771
01:28:30,590 --> 01:28:31,682
ln Gradov?

772
01:28:31,758 --> 01:28:32,747
Yes.

773
01:28:33,994 --> 01:28:35,086
l'll be all right.

774
01:28:35,162 --> 01:28:36,823
l wish l could think so.

775
01:28:42,736 --> 01:28:44,397
